Well! Where to begin? Just touched back down after a couple blissful weeks on cloud 9.

The beauty of the human spirit and the places we have visited have been utterly overwhelming. 

I am excited to share our recent joy while also needing to hold these moments close to my heart. 

I feel wrapped up in sweet contentment, and truthfully a little fearful that an attempt to share will fall short of the wonder we have witnessed. 

How can I properly express my immense gratitude, the awe inspiring power of nature, and the incredible goodness in people without sounding insincere or superfluous? 

This is an odd new feeling for a gal who loves taking photos and creating imagery. But a tiny voice on this recent adventure has been impossible to ignore— and while I want to share it all. I need to properly recognize the people and places that have come into our life.

In the coming weeks, moments from the Catskills to Sambi Sands will be mixed in with my regular beautiful clients, but I am challenging myself to post slowly and with greater intention. I hope that I can reflect on the magic of humanity— what makes life precious, our planet worth protecting and our relationships so important to nurture.

So— this has been a lot of words for a super visual gal, thanks for baring with me… while I continue to collect my thoughts and express my gratitude, shall I begin with the beautiful fleurs of the Catskills the week of our wedding at Foxfire Mountain House to which I owe many many thanks to the brilliant mind and care of Nikki @stregaflora 

Nikki— you were an angel and a dream come true. Thank you for your art and loving flowers as much if not more than I do! You created our wonderland.

Capetown was extraordinary. Going into the trip, several friends told me it was their favorite city on earth, but I still couldn’t wrap my head around what to expect. 

A mountain as it’s centerpiece, a delicious food scene, beaches everywhere— all these help argue the case. 2 weeks later, I am moved by all we learned from our generous guide Thomas Nzenzo at Africa Gateway Travel who helped us dive beyond the surface to experience Capetown. 

Thomas was a wealth of knowledge on every front imaginable. He made a special stop at the Kirstenboesch Gardens when he heard about my passion for flowers so we could learn about the unique biosphere of Capetown— the Fynbos, where Protea grow wild, and the weather can be predicted by looking our at the sky above the oceans. 

He shared the history of South Africa from before the Age of Exploration through Nelson Mandela’s lifetime into modern day. He impressed upon us, with passion and honesty, the necessities and fragility of democracy, freedom, tolerance and conversation. 

He was passionate about which wineries have the best Shiraz, Pinotage, Chenin Blanc and how to pair them with chocolate and even made sure we were well acquainted with the terrain so we would have the best hike up to the Top of #TableMountain.

We owe a debt of gratitude to Thomas, and I can’t help but believe he also embodied the spirit of #SouthAfrica and Capetown, allowing me to understand why #Capetown hold’s such a special place in the heart of so many and deserves a spot of the list of the worlds most wonderful cities.

Our next stop was Franschhoek, in South Africa’s wine country.
This quaint corner of the country offered incredible dining (we had divine meals at @epice_franschhoek and @protegerestaurant ), sweeping views of the mountainside, independently owned boutiques, stunning art galleries and unbelievable wine.
I could have moved into @stay_lacle — our picturesque bed and breakfast where they spoiled us rotten with fresh fruits, homemade pastries, and wine from their own vineyard.
It was at the vineyards of @mlfwines and @grandeprovence where we had our first sips of #Pinotage— the signature red wine of South Africa and we’re absolutely spoiled with a chocolate and wine pairing at the @waterford_estate .
We only had 3 days in #Franschhoek, but the charm and romance of this region captured our hearts— we could have stayed 3 weeks!

Our final stop was #sabisands . We stayed at @simbambiligamelodge — named for 2 Lions the Founder encountered in the brush. An apt name as wildlife wanders through the property at any moment. 

Sitting on the deck of our room we observed giraffe, elephants, warthogs, impalas, kudu, herons, etc. We were told a leopard gave birth in the dining room just months before.

While the grounds at the lodge were breathtaking, I was struck by was the care and attention of the team at #Simbambili .

Glory looked after us. She radiated warmth, remembered all of our likes and nuances. With Glory, I had the feeling of spending time with a relative that puts everyone at ease. Returning home— I hope to bring her care and kindness with me. She reminded me, that to look after others, to nurture is a great gift. 

On the game drives, Lazarus (guide) & Roy (tracker) went above & beyond to give us a life changing experience.  With expert knowledge, they not only made sure we saw and understood the lives of the Big 5 animals, but helped us to understand the story of the animals by following the same pride/herd/pack every day so we could understand the unique qualities and needs of each animal.

Lazarus had been with Simbambili since the building of the lodge- 25 years ago. His enthusiasm, love and knowledge was evident immediately. Laz helped to reignite passion for the wild, instilling a deep desire to do whatever possible to protect this planet and it’s creatures. With him and Roy, we were feet away from Leopards, Lions— a Rhino took a rest on our vehicle, and we observed a herd of over 1000 buffalo. The majesty of animals was breathtaking and will forever shape our lives.
